---
/**
 * Methodology Page - Explains the Hunter research process
 *
 * Transparency page explaining how StackHunt researches and evaluates tools.
 * Critical for building EEAT (Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness)
 * when individual human authors are unavailable.
 *
 * @module pages/methodology
 */

import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  meta={{
    title: "Research Methodology | StackHunt",
    description: "Learn how StackHunt researches, evaluates, and verifies software recommendations using AI-powered analysis and human oversight.",
    canonical: "https://stackhunt.co/methodology"
  }}
>
  <div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none prose-headings:text-zinc-100 prose-p:text-zinc-400 prose-a:text-indigo-400 hover:prose-a:text-indigo-300 prose-strong:text-zinc-200 prose-li:text-zinc-400">
      <h1>How StackHunt Works</h1>

      <p class="lead text-xl text-zinc-400">
        We use AI to research, humans to verify. Every recommendation is backed by sources,
        and every claim is verifiable. Here's exactly how our process works.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border border-indigo-500/20 bg-indigo-500/10 p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <svg class="h-6 w-6 flex-shrink-0 text-indigo-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-100">Our Commitment</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
              We use AI to research at scale, but we don't blindly trust it. Every tool review
              is created as a draft, verified for accuracy, and linked to original sources.
              We clearly label opinions and distinguish them from facts.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>The "Hunter" Research Process</h2>

      <p>
        StackHunt uses a three-phase pipeline we call "The Hunter" to research and evaluate
        software tools. The entire process is automated for efficiency, but designed with
        human verification in mind.
      </p>

      <h3>Phase 1: Research (The Scout)</h3>

      <p>
        When we research a tool, we don't just look at the official website. We run
        <strong>12 parallel Google searches</strong> to gather comprehensive information
        from multiple perspectives:
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-zinc-100">Factual Queries (6)</h4>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            <li>• User reviews and feedback</li>
            <li>• Pricing plans and features</li>
            <li>• Annual vs monthly pricing comparison</li>
            <li>• Alternatives and competitors</li>
            <li>• Company info (funding, history)</li>
            <li>• Technical capabilities (API, integrations)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-zinc-100">Tribal Knowledge (6)</h4>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            <li>• Hidden costs and billing gotchas</li>
            <li>• Implementation and setup fees</li>
            <li>• Reddit reviews and honest feedback</li>
            <li>• "What I wish I knew before" insights</li>
            <li>• Power user tips and shortcuts</li>
            <li>• "Is it worth it?" discussions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        In addition to search snippets, we perform <strong>deep scraping</strong> of
        official pricing pages to capture full pricing tables, tier comparisons, and
        fine print that might not appear in search results.
      </p>

      <p>
        We also search for relevant YouTube videos (demos, tutorials, reviews) to
        provide visual context for users who prefer video content.
      </p>

      <h3>Phase 2: Analysis (Two-Pass AI Synthesis)</h3>

      <p>
        Once we've gathered information, we use Google's Gemini 2.0 Flash to analyze
        it in two distinct passes:
      </p>

      <h4>Pass 1: The Librarian (Knowledge Card Extraction)</h4>

      <p>
        The first pass acts as a meticulous fact-checker. It extracts structured,
        verifiable information:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Core features</strong> - What the tool does</li>
        <li><strong>Pricing tiers</strong> - Plans, costs, billing cycles</li>
        <li><strong>Platform support</strong> - Web, mobile, desktop availability</li>
        <li><strong>Integrations</strong> - Connected apps and services</li>
        <li><strong>Company information</strong> - Founded, headquarters, funding stage</li>
        <li><strong>Competitors</strong> - Main alternatives in the market</li>
        <li><strong>Learning curve</strong> - Time to become productive</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        This pass focuses on <em>facts</em>, not opinions. Everything must be
        verifiable from the search results.
      </p>

      <h4>Pass 2: The Architect (Contextual Synthesis)</h4>

      <p>
        The second pass synthesizes a contextual review that goes beyond the spec sheet.
        It wears three "hats" to provide different perspectives:
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 space-y-4">
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-4">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <div class="flex h-10 w-10 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-blue-500/10">
              <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-blue-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8c-1.657 0-3 .895-3 2s1.343 2 3 2 3 .895 3 2-1.343 2-3 2m0-8c1.11 0 2.08.402 2.599 1M12 8V7m0 1v8m0 0v1m0-1c-1.11 0-2.08-.402-2.599-1" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h5 class="font-semibold text-zinc-100">The Budget Analyst</h5>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Explains the total cost of ownership without judgment. Identifies cost drivers,
                one-time fees, commitment terms, and when the premium tier becomes worth it.
                No "gotcha" language - just facts about how the bill works.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-4">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <div class="flex h-10 w-10 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-purple-500/10">
              <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-purple-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M17 20h5v-2a3 3 0 00-5.356-1.857M17 20H7m10 0v-2c0-.656-.126-1.283-.356-1.857M7 20H2v-2a3 3 0 015.356-1.857M7 20v-2c0-.656.126-1.283.356-1.857m0 0a5.002 5.002 0 019.288 0M15 7a3 3 0 11-6 0 3 3 0 016 0zm6 3a2 2 0 11-4 0 2 2 0 014 0zM7 10a2 2 0 11-4 0 2 2 0 014 0z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h5 class="font-semibold text-zinc-100">The User Advocate</h5>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Captures the "vibe" and tribal knowledge. Who's it ideal for? Who should avoid it?
                What do power users love? What are common frustrations? Includes insider tips
                from Reddit, forums, and community discussions.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-4">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <div class="flex h-10 w-10 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-green-500/10">
              <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-green-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.663 17h4.673M12 3v1m6.364 1.636l-.707.707M21 12h-1M4 12H3m3.343-5.657l-.707-.707m2.828 9.9a5 5 0 117.072 0l-.548.547A3.374 3.374 0 0014 18.469V19a2 2 0 11-4 0v-.531c0-.895-.356-1.754-.988-2.386l-.548-.547z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <h5 class="font-semibold text-zinc-100">The Human Verdict</h5>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                A plain-English summary in "Coffee Shop Speak" - no corporate jargon like
                "seamless," "empowers," or "robust." Just honest, clear language about what
                this tool actually does and who it's best for.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Every pro and con includes three pieces of metadata for legal protection and transparency:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>source_url</strong> - The exact URL where this claim is supported</li>
        <li><strong>source_type</strong> - Official website, editorial review, or community discussion</li>
        <li><strong>claim_type</strong> - Fact (verifiable) or opinion (subjective)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Phase 3: Persistence (Draft-First Publishing)</h3>

      <p>
        After analysis, we don't immediately publish. Instead, we:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Create a draft review</strong> - Every review starts unpublished</li>
        <li><strong>Upsert the tool</strong> - Add to our database with metadata and knowledge card</li>
        <li><strong>Link to sources</strong> - Store all citation URLs for verification</li>
        <li><strong>Human verification</strong> - Our team reviews before publishing</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        This draft-first workflow ensures that AI-generated content is always verified
        by humans before it reaches our users.
      </p>

      <h2>Source Attribution & Legal Protection</h2>

      <p>
        Every claim on StackHunt is linked to its source. We classify sources into three
        categories to help you assess credibility:
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3 rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-3">
          <div class="flex h-8 w-8 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded bg-green-500/10">
            <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-green-400">OFF</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-medium text-zinc-100">Official Sources</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-zinc-400">
              The tool's own website, blog, documentation, or official announcements.
              Highest authority for factual claims about features and pricing.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex items-start gap-3 rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-3">
          <div class="flex h-8 w-8 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded bg-blue-500/10">
            <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-blue-400">EDI</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-medium text-zinc-100">Editorial Sources</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-zinc-400">
              Professional review sites (G2, Capterra, Gartner) and tech publications
              (PCMag, TechRadar). Can include both facts and expert opinions.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex items-start gap-3 rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-3">
          <div class="flex h-8 w-8 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded bg-purple-500/10">
            <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-purple-400">COM</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-medium text-zinc-100">Community Sources</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-zinc-400">
              Reddit discussions, HackerNews threads, user forums, and personal blogs.
              Valuable for "vibe" and real-world experiences, but subjective by nature.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Data Freshness Policy</h2>

      <p>
        Software changes fast. Pricing updates, features get added, companies get acquired.
        Here's how we keep information current:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Verification dates</strong> - Every tool page shows when it was last verified
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stale data alerts</strong> - If data is over 60 days old, we display a warning banner
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Community verification</strong> - Users can report outdated information, which
          automatically queues the tool for re-research
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Automatic re-hunts</strong> - High-traffic tools are periodically re-researched
          to ensure accuracy
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What We Don't Do</h2>

      <p>
        Transparency includes being clear about our limitations:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't test tools hands-on</strong> - Our reviews are based on publicly
          available information, not direct usage. This means we can cover more tools, but
          can't provide first-hand experience insights.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't contact vendors</strong> - All information comes from public sources
          (websites, reviews, community discussions). We don't get special access or briefings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't have NDAs or partnerships</strong> - We maintain editorial independence
          by not entering into special relationships with vendors (beyond standard affiliate programs).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We can't guarantee 100% accuracy</strong> - We verify everything we can, but
          software changes rapidly and sources can be outdated or incorrect. If you spot an error,
          please let us know.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Report Inaccuracies</h2>

      <p>
        Found something wrong? We take corrections seriously. Every report is reviewed,
        and if we confirm an error, we'll update the content and re-verify the tool.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="/corrections" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-indigo-500 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-indigo-600 transition no-underline">
          Submit a correction
          <svg class="h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 7l5 5m0 0l-5 5m5-5H6" />
          </svg>
        </a>
      </p>

      <hr class="my-8" />

      <div class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-6">
        <h3 class="mt-0 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-100">Questions About Our Process?</h3>
        <p class="mb-0 text-sm text-zinc-400">
          We're happy to clarify how we research tools, verify information, or handle
          corrections. Our methodology is designed to be transparent and continuously improving.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500">
        Last updated: {new Date().toLocaleDateString('en-US', { month: 'long', day: 'numeric', year: 'numeric' })}
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
